  "unmapped_findings": [
    "SPP (strength-plasticity product) for R650: 16.5 ± 1.5 GPa%, R750: 12.5 ± 2.6 GPa%, R850: 9.6 ± 0.1 GPa%, R950: 4.4 ± 1.0 GPa%.",
    "R650 impact crack initiation energy Ei = 59.6 J, propagation energy Ep = 147.9 J; R750 Ep = 51.51 J, indicating dominant role of propagation resistance.",
    "R850 and R950 impact curves show steep single peak with almost no Ei or Ep, indicating unstable crack propagation immediately after initiation.",
    "Low-temperature rolling zone (R650, R750) exhibits DRV (dynamic recovery) as dominant softening mechanism with high KAM values; high-temperature rolling zone (R850, R950) dominated by DRX (dynamic recrystallization) and DIFT, leading to HAGBs increase and dislocation density decrease.",
    "Carbide precipitation mechanism: during low-temperature rolling, martensite decomposes, C, Mn, Cr diffuse to defect sites and precipitate as M3C, M23C6, M7C7; Ostwald ripening at higher temperature coarsens carbides.",
    "R650 fracture mode: mixed ductile fracture with crack blunting, deflection, and microvoid-induced horizontal propagation; tensile fracture shows delamination serrated morphology.",
    "Orowan mechanism: carbides with diameter >10 nm pin dislocations, enhancing work hardening; nanoscale spherical carbides increase crack tip curvature radius and blunt crack, reducing stress concentration.",
    "Bonding force at carbide/ferrite interface is greater than at ferrite/ferrite interface, preventing crack propagation through carbide-containing lamellae.",
    "In high-temperature rolling zone, hardness mismatch martensite/δ-ferrite >3.3 GPa causes interfacial stress concentration; DIF grains act as pre-fabricated crack paths.",
    "Figure 4: EBSD maps (GB+GOS, KAM, IPF, nanoindentation) for all samples; Figure 5: mechanical properties including impact energy vs temperature, load-displacement curves, engineering stress-strain curves, work hardening rate curves; Figure 6: phase diagrams; Figure 7: TEM/EDS of R650 carbides; Figure 8: impact and tensile fracture morphology of R650; Figure 9: TEM/HRTEM of R650 and fracture schematics for all samples. Pure text pipeline does not include image pixel data.",
    "The tested steel was fabricated via VIM (vacuum induction melting); ingot homogenized at 1200 °C for 4 h, hot forged to 40 mm, then cut into specimens.",
    "Tensile specimen gauge length 25 mm, diameter 5 mm; crosshead speed 1.5 mm/min; Charpy specimen 10×10×55 mm, V-notch, impact direction perpendicular to RD."
  ]
